div.p: This model is described in the article:

div.a: Motor neuron-immune interactions: The vicious circle of ALS.

div.div: Barbeito AG, Mesci P, Boill√©e S.

div.p:
Because microglial cells, the resident macrophages of the CNS, react to any lesion of the nervous system,
they have for long been regarded as potential players in the pathogenesis of several neurodegenerative disorders including amyotrophic lateral sclerosis,
the most common motor neuron disease in the adult.
In recent years, this microglial reaction to motor neuron injury, in particular, and the innate immune response, in general,
has been implicated in the progression of the disease, in mouse models of ALS.
The mechanisms by which microglial cells influence motor neuron death in ALS are still largely unknown.
Microglial activation increases over the course of the disease and is associated with an alteration in the production of toxic factors and also
neurotrophic factors.
Adding to the microglial/macrophage response to motor neuron degeneration, the adaptive immune system can likewise influence the disease process.
Exploring these motor neuron-immune interactions could lead to a better understanding in the physiopathology of ALS to find
new pathways to slow down motor neuron degeneration.

notes.body:
A motor unit is made up of a motor neuron and the skeletal muscle fibers innervated by that motor neuron's axonal terminals.
Groups of motor units often work together to coordinate the contractions of a single muscle.
All of the motor units within a muscle are considered a motor pool.

Surviving Upper neurons
Upper motor neurons are found in the brain and carry motor information down the spinal cord to activate the lower motor neurons,

Dead Upper neurons
Upper motor neurons are found in the brain and carry motor information down the spinal cord to activate the lower motor neurons,

Surviving lower motor neurons
The efferent fiber carries nerve impulses away from the the spinal cord, and toward the muscles.

Dead lower motor neurons
The efferent fiber carries nerve impulses away from the the spinal cord, and toward the muscles.

They are the largest type of leukocyte and can differentiate into macrophages and myeloid lineage dendritic cells.
Monocytes can differentiate into dendritic cells by adding the cytokines granulocyte macrophage colony-stimulating factor (GM-CSF) and interleukin 4.

B cells, also known as B lymphocytes, are a type of white blood cell.
* They secrete antibodies.
* B cells are also classified as professional antigen-presenting cells (APCs)).
* B cells secrete cytokines.

T cell, or T lymphocyte, is a type of lymphocyte that plays a central role in cell-mediated immunity.
They mature in the thymus which "selects for" T cells capable of interacting with MHC, and kill the "non-self" cells.
On can further categorize T cells in:
* Cytotoxic T cells (CD8+ T cells)
* Helper T cells (CD4+ T cells)
* Regulatory T cells
* Natural Killer T cells

Dendritic cells are antigen-presenting cells. They process ("eat") material found in the ECM and present it to the T cells.
They act as messengers between the innate and the adaptive immune systems.
